    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my civil eng exam and im a bit confused. if concrete is already really strong, why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside it for foundations? like what is the actual relationship between the compressive strength of the concrete and the tensile strength of the steel?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The reason we use steel rebar in concrete foundations is to provide tensile strength, which is a different property than compressive strength. Concrete has high compressive strength, but it can't withstand tensile forces, which are forces that stretch or pull apart a material. Steel rebar, on the other hand, has high tensile strength, which allows it to resist these forces. In essence, the rebar acts as a reinforcement, allowing the concrete to distribute loads more evenly and resist cracking. This is a key principle in reinforced concrete design.",
      "source": "target",
